&lt;p&gt;This article gives a quick overview over the feedforward phase of a Neural Network.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id="nodes"&gt;Nodes&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;A Neural Network is made of many &lt;strong&gt;Nodes&lt;/strong&gt; that are connected to each other. Each Node itself is a very basic unit that does only do three things.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ol&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Multiply each input with a weight and sum all inputs up. $y_{in} = \sum_{i=0}^m w_i\cdot x_i$, where $m$ is the number of inputs.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Process the single, scalar input value by some activation function $y_{out}=f(y_{in})$ where $y_{in}$ is the result from step 1 and $y_{out}$ is the result from step 1 after being applied to the activation function.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Output the result $y_{out}$ to the next node&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;
&lt;p&gt;So, a single node pretty much looks like this:
